A feeling of general discomfort, weakness, or lack of health.
Anomalous structure of a blood vessel in the kidney.
An anomalous structure of an artery located in the kidney.
Anomalous structure of the arc-shaped arteries located at the border of the renal cortex and renal medulla.
A state of feeling very unhappy, uneasy, or dissatisfied.
An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to one or both testes.

An inner sense (from the self) that thoughts are moving abnormally fast and in a manner that the individual typically feels that the rate is beyond their control, i.e. they feel unable to slow the rate of thoughts. Racing thoughts by themselves have a linear progression, following a line of thinking or logic, which distinguishes racing thoughts from flight of ideas. Racing thoughts may however, co-occur with or be independent from flight of ideas, they may be associated with pressured speech or be an internal perception of the rate of thinking. The core element being the rate of the thoughts themselves.
A feeling that something life-threatening or tragic is about to occur.
A form of altered taste sensation in which the affected person perceives a taste, usually an unpleasant one, in the absence of a corresponding stimulus in the environment.
Any structural anomaly located in the the inside space of the interlobular veins of the kidney.

label.value: Cortical peritubular capillary lumen cholesterol emboli

definition.value: Needle-like or slit-like clefts within the interior space of peritubular capillaries located in the cortex of the kidney. Cholesterol emboli are visualized as clear spaces (cholesterol clefts) where the cholesterol crystals have been dissolved by routine processing. Acute lesions can be accompanied by inflammation and fibrin.
Mixture of fibrin, red blood cells, platelets partly or completely occluding the vascular lumen of the peritubular capillaries located in the cortex of the kidney.
